* '''[[1963 in literature|1964]]:''' No award given{{efn|group=notes|&quot;Among the books the judges most seriously considered were the following: (1) [[Norman Fruchter]]'s ''Coat Upon a Stick''…, (2) [[May Sarton]]'s novella ''Joanna and Ulysses''…, (3) [[Sumner Locke Elliott]]'s ''[[Careful, He Might Hear You (novel)|Careful, He Might Hear You]]''…, [and] (4) [[John Killens]]' ''And Then We Heard the Thunder''… If a prize were to be awarded for a 1963 novel we felt these to be the most serious candidates.&quot; However, the fiction jury ultimately recommended that no award be given because &quot;no one of them imposes itself upon us as demanding recognition as 'distinguished fiction'….&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;hohenberg&quot; /&gt;}}
** ''Coat Upon a Stick'' by [[Norman Fruchter]]
** ''Joanna and Ulysses'' by [[May Sarton]]
